\begin_layout Standard
There have only been a small number of attempts at modeling the dynamics of snow crab populations. Being long-lived, sexually dimorphic, deep water, benthic organisms, usually living far offshore, they are not easily surveyed. Snow crab have a complex life history that spans up to 15 years from planktonic to benthic stages. They molt 2 times a year in the early stages and then approximately annually by instar 5 (about 15 mm carapace width) and can even skip molts when living conditions are poor. This life history complexity causes complexity in their dynamics and spatial distributions. Most population assessments approach abundance estimation as a fishery- or survey-based relative index of a narrow segment of the population (the fishable component). When modeled, these empirical estimates of abundance are assumed to be known without bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, aging of snow crab is not possible due to a lack of retention of calcified body parts through molts. This has encouraged adoption of size-based models 
