name "logistic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Verhulst's original formulation of the logistic equation was used to model Belgium's population growth 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
{
\end_layout

\end_inset

(Verhulst 1845, Bacaër 2011)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
}
\end_layout

\end_inset

. His arguments alluded to Malthusian geometric (exponential) growth with some upper limit. The intrinsic rate of increase (r) representing the exponential rate of increase while carrying capacity (K) represented this limit. Subsequently 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "McKendrick_Pai_1912"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used it for bacterial growth and then 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "Pearl_Reed_1920, Lotka_1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used it for the US population. It continues to be used today in numerous fields due to its underlying sigmoid shape 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "Beverton_Holt_1957, Pianka_1970, Bohner_Chieochan_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lotka 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "Lotka_1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recognized that the logistic equation can more simply be seen as a 2nd order Taylor series approximation of any general function 
\begin_inset Formula ${\frac{\mathit{dN}}{\mathit{dt}}_{}=G}{(N)}$
\end_inset

, evaluated at N=0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O{(N^{h})}$
\end_inset

 are higher order terms greater of power h
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
textgreater
\end_layout

\end_inset

2: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\frac{\mathit{dN}}{\mathit{dt}}_{}=\mathit{rN}}-{({rK^{-1}})}{N^{2}+O}{(N^{h})}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pianka 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "Pianka_1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (in Fig. 9.5 of his paper) suggested a slightly different perspective on the logistic equation. He begins with birth and death rates that are linear functions of abundance: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\beta=\beta}_{0}-\mathit{eN}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta={\delta_{0}+\mathit{fN}}$
\end_inset

. At equilibrium, K, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\delta$
\end_inset

 due to the intersection of the lines, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula ${\beta_{0}-\mathit{eK}}={\delta_{0}+\mathit{fK}}$
\end_inset

, and so: 
\begin_inset Formula ${r_{0}={\beta_{0}-\delta_{0}}={({e-f})}}K$
\end_inset

. Away from equilibrium, after some algebra, we obtain the logistic equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathit{dN}}{\mathit{dt}}_{}=\mathit{rN}={{({{({\beta{0-\mathit{eN}}})}-{({\delta_{0}+\mathit{fN}})}})}{N=r_{0}}{N-r_{0}}N^{2}.}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, the sigmoid Beverton-Holt difference equation has also been shown to be related to the logistic equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
before ""
key "Beverton_Holt_1957, Bohner_Chieochan_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula ${n_{t+1}=\frac{\nu Kn_{t}}{{K_{t}+{({\nu-1})}}n_{t}}}.$
\end_inset

 It is discrete in time and also sigmoid in shape with asymptotic limit (carrying capacity that varies with time) 
\begin_inset Formula ${K_{t}}>0$
\end_inset

 and growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>1$
\end_inset

, for number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}>0$
\end_inset

. If we define: 
\begin_inset Formula $r={{({\nu-1})}/\nu}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu={1/{({1-r})}}$
\end_inset

, then substitution and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula ${\Delta n}_{t}$
\end_inset

 gives: 
\begin_inset Formula ${{\Delta n}_{t}=r}n_{t+1}{{({K_{t}-n_{t+1}})}/{({{K_{t}-r}n_{t+1}})}},$
\end_inset

 which simplifies further to the discrete logistic difference equation: 
\begin_inset Formula ${{\Delta n}_{t}=r}n_{t+1}{({1-{n_{t}/K_{t}}})}$
\end_inset

. In the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, this becomes the differential form of the logistic equation: 
\begin_inset Formula ${{{\mathit{dn}/\mathit{dt}}=\mathit{rn}}{({1-{n/K_{t}}})}.}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, another similar model, the 
\emph on
logistic discrete map
\emph default
, could be used for parameter estimation. The 
\emph on
discrete logistic map
\emph default
 is often represented as a Euler approximation of the logistic differential equation, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\frac{\mathit{dZ}}{\mathit{dt}}=r}Z{({{1-Z}K^{-1}})}$
\end_inset

. Normalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z={Z/K}$
\end_inset

 allows simplification to: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\frac{\mathit{dz}}{\mathit{dt}}=r}z{({1-z})}.$
\end_inset

 The Euler approximation for a small increment of time 
\begin_inset Formula ${\tau_{t+1}={\tau_{t}+\Delta}}\tau$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 in the next time interval is estimated as: 
\begin_inset Formula ${z_{t+1}={z_{t}+\Delta}}\tau\cdot\frac{\mathit{dz}}{\mathit{dt}}{}_{z_{t}}$
\end_inset

, which upon substitution of the differential equation and simplification gives: 
\begin_inset Formula ${z_{t+1}={({{1+\Delta}\tau r})}}{z_{t}-\Delta}\tau r{z_{t}}^{2}$
\end_inset

. The identities: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rho={1+\Delta}}\tau r,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${n_{t}=\frac{\Delta\tau rz_{t}}{\rho}},$
\end_inset

 help to simplify further: 
\begin_inset Formula ${n_{t+1}=\frac{\Delta\tau rz_{t+1}}{\rho}}.$
\end_inset

 Substitution of the identity of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 to gives: 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t+1}={}$
